or taking the time for such a thoughtful response. I fear I have not made myself clear. I completely agree with your analysis of climate stability; a good display of your clear understanding and knowledge. My point about systemic failure was aimed at human productive and logistical networks. In the U.K. a few years ago (forgive me I don\u2019t know where you are from) the strike by fuel tanker drivers threaten food distribution. Indeed the strike became a threat to the fuel distribution network, posing hazard of a feedback induced logical failure.  When considering the huge network of interconnected systems that are needed to maintain productive and distributive capacity, it seems to me that there are a wide variety of vulnerabilities. Even a failure of an unreal system such as banking could lead to the loss of mutual exchange of goods and consequent disaster.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113266356", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "even a failure of an unreal system such as banking", "effect": "the loss of mutual exchange of goods and consequent disaster"}]}, {"id": "113266356", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520513463000}, "author": "100suns", "author_id": "13299353", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Computer systems are the canonical example of things which are extremely brittle: in a simple-minded computer system a significant proportion of physical changes which get large enough to flip a single bit will cause catastrophic failure of the system.\nSome physical systems (computers are physical systems of course: if I had more space I would describe the difference more carefully) also have this kind of property, usually known as chaos or sensitive dependence on initial conditions (SDIC): tiny changes get blown up into huge later changes in the system. Weather, famously, is one such (which is why exponential increases in the computing power we can put into forecasting weather only result in roughly linear improvements in the time we can forecast it for).\nClimate does not seem to be one of those systems: small changes in forcings tend to result in small changes to the climate. I am not sure if we understand mathematically why that is, or whether there are regions of the phase space of climate where there is SDIC (there almost certainly are: see below). But we have at least two sorts of experimental evidence that the climate is well-behaved in this sense: first of all we have quite good records of the way the climate behaved in the past, in particular during several cycles of glaciations & deglaciations, and it didn't fall off any cliffs, even when the total temperature swings were ~10 degrees. Secondly we can look around us and see life, and life depends on the climate not continually lashing about: trees, for instance, depend on changes being slow because they can't get up and walk to where the climate is more suitable for them, but have to creep around over hundreds or thousands of years by growing child trees in better places. And there are a lot of trees.\nNone of this means that there are not regions in the phase space where the climate does lash around wildly: as I said, almost certainly there are. But there's no real evidence that we're close to such a region. The most worrying thing is that we're pushing change into the system at a rate much faster than it has happened, almost ever (the event that killed the dinosaurs was faster: things like ice-ages were much slower, as was the PETM).\nAnd even assuming the climate does not fall off a cliff in some way, the results of the changes driven by us are still very bad, of course.\nIn response to your comment about the US and food security: yes, obviously the US will not be the first country where a lot of people starve after harvests fail. They just might be the first one with a significant nuclear capability though, which was my point: no-one will care that billion poor people starve, they will care when a few million rich people do.", "r