relations": null}, {"id": "113054778", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520148428000}, "author": "Continentalcyclist", "author_id": "11797417", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I am aware of the use of heat pumps. They have an important part to play. And they do in this country. As does thermal and PV solar.\nBut heat pumps are only one element of the future. They require vast amounts of electricity throughout the winter cycle. Even a minergy standard home, of which there are virtually none in Britain, will require 3000 kWh per heating season. Or 20 kWh per day on an average winter day. Or 30 kWh on a cold day. When the grid is creaking. By comparison our entire domestic electricity consumption per year is 1800 kWh. And many homes here produce more eletricity than they use.\nPresumable, in addition to the mass use of heat pumps, you also want electrical cars. How are you going to cope?\nYour claims on emissions are wrong. For one thing carbon monoxiode is highly toxic, but not a greenhouse gas. Carbon dioxide is. It is the result of incomplete combustion. State-of-the-art wood burning does not produce methane. Methane emissions are also the result of incomplete combustion, ie incomplete chemical reduction because of insufficient temperatures and oxygen input. \nYou need to check your chemistry. If you knew German I would refer you to the association of Swiss oven builders and their computer modulations requisite for every single oven installed.\nThe same holds for black carbon. It is fuel emitted unburnt.\nYou refer to 'domestic heaters\u2019. Again you are unaware of the technologies developed in Germany, Austria, Switzerland and elsewhere. We do not use Villagers or Agas.\nThere is no single fix to the energy and climate future. In the building sector heat pumps are one very important element. But they require an awful lot of electrical power, in winter, when it is least available. I have a fairly good grasp on the capacities of the Alpine storage batteries in winter and know their limitations, as well as the limitations of the grid in Continental Europe. In Britain the situation is much worse. Without interconnectors to the Continent, Norway and Ireland, the UK cannot install sufficient heat pump capacity. Particularly as long as it still exports waste to Oslo (of all places) to heat the homes in Norway, in combination with electricity generation and steam for industries. With plenty of oil, gas, and hydro electricity available.\nWe are far ahead of the UK in combined heating systems in cities, from waste burning, sewage treatment plants, geothermal, and waste heat from industries, office servers and cooling systems. And wood there plays a part, as woodchips, pellets, and logs. Whereas Britain still does landfills, with huge amounts of uncaptured methane emissions. They are extremely potent climate agents.\nIn new homes we need no outside heating input at all. Solar with a one hundred cubic metre boiler will do.\nBut the real crunch is the combustion engine, road transport. Urban transit systems, trains, trams, trolleybuses on renewable electricity, cycling, walking, planning reducing commuter distances: that is where the music plays. And air transport. Why airline kerosene is untaxed is difficult to convey.\nTunnel vision will not do. Check your science, check your energy computations, look at the entire picture, and then come back.\nOr build one hundred nuclear power plants in the UK. Within the next five to ten years. Just how? Is that your agenda?", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "113053993", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "insufficient temperatures and oxygen input", "effect": "methane emissions are also the result of incomplete combustion ie incomplete chemical reduction"}]}, {"id": "113053993", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520144509000}, "author": "EnviroSci", "author_id": "4386683", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Wood stoves produce black carbon, methane and carbon monoxide, all of which are very powerful greenhouse pollutants that cause a lot more global warming than the CO2 from the stove. Over the next 20 years (the critical period if we are to achieve the target set at Paris of keeping global warming well below 2 degrees), heating a house with a wood stove will cause more global warming than a dozen similar houses heated by modern, efficient, electric heat pumps (also called reverse cycle air conditioners).\nThis means that burning wood in domestic heaters can never be climate-friendly any more than a simple 30,000 volt electrode can clean up more that a fraction of the pollution from the average wood stove.\nModern, efficient heat pumps have superseded wood stoves and natural gas as the most cost-effective climate-friendly heating. The most efficient model can deliver 5 times as much heat to the home as it uses in electric power, even when the outside temperature is 5 degrees below freezing. They are affordable (as cheap as buying a wood stove) and have lower running costs than buying firewood and in addition to causing only a tiny fraction of the global warming, they don't damage our health. For a detailed analysis, see woodsmoke 3sc net/ghg (replace spaces with dots).", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "113042841", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "that", "effect": "a lot more global warming than the co2"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "more global warming than a dozen similar houses heated by modern pumps"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "only a tiny fraction of the global warming"}]}, {"id": "112947690", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1519956745000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "You might win that one.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "112947627", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "112947627", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1519956468000}, "author": "Shanesw", "author_id": "17473764", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "te