lance over one year is neutral. And incidentally dead wood rotting will release the same amount of carbon as will wood used for heating, unless it is buried and sealed in the ground, turning to peat and eventually coal under water in moors. \nSustainable forestry prevails across the European Alps. In fact more wood grows (and eventually decomposes unless used) than is harvested. Heating with woodchips and pellets therefore makes sense. And so do log fires with state-of-the-art burning facilities ensuring high temperatures and a sufficient oxygen supply to ensure a complete chemical reduction. \nAny burning of coal and oil will release all the carbon extracted from the earth into the atmosphere, and even supposedly environment friendly gas contains considerable amounts of carbon which is released as carbon dioxide upon burning.\nIn sustainable forestry the very same amount of carbon dioxide is released by burning or rotting as is split up into carbon and oxygen and thus turned into wood by photosynthesis in the same annual cycle, reducing the carbon dioxide to carbon and oxygen. It is hence carbon neutral. And has been for millenia. In fact since the last ice age. When forests began to grow.\nSo, given sustainable forestry, with the same amount of wood growing as is used, heating with wood will be carbon neutral. Coal, oil and gas will not.\nOur area has the highest amount of timber per hectare of forest in Europe: 400 cubic metres. It also has a lot of biodiversity, with a mix of many kinds of trees, as well as a mix of old and young trees side by side. The maximum amount of trees foresters are allowed to cut in any area is defined by the height of the trees. With trees measuring a length of 25 m, a circle of at the most 50 m diametres may be cut. But mostly individual trees will be taken out, providing space and light for the others and for saplings to grow naturally. Called ungleich verj\u00fcngter Blenterwald.\nIn many areas chimneys are equipped with filtres. Our chimney has a steel tube with a 30,000 Volt DC electrode magnetising any unburnt soot particles, which will then settle on the steel tube, where the chimney sweep will vacuum them up.\nThe claims made by the article are unsustainable. They only apply if forests are cut down wholesale, as they will be for cattle grazing or soy bean production, or for coconut palms. Instead of castigating wood burners, the authors might have pointed out the effects of meat production in Brazil. Or beef, pork or chicken production and consumption in our parts, with soy beans used as fodder.\nBurning wood alongside sustainable forestry is climate friendly. The statement above to the contrary else is untenable. Eat less meat if you wish to reduce carbon dioxide emissions. In the process you will also lower methane emissions by cattle. And methane is a far for potent climate gas than carbon dioxide.", "recommendation_count": "2", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "112947446", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1519955724000}, "author": "djw300", "author_id": "2947349", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I'm astounded that after years of trying to clean the environment and banning domestic fires, wood burning heaters have been allowed to become popular. The pollution they throw out is significant, not only for those in and around them in the home, but also to anybody who lives nearby.", "recommendation_count": "10", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "112947215", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1519954813000}, "author": "R Anon", "author_id": "17206208", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Guess what's causing increased extreme weather events [electrical storms], yep AGW. Guess whats causing AGW, clues in the name A= anthropogenic.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "112944685", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "what", "effect": "increased extreme weather events storms"}, {"cause": "what", "effect": "agw"}]}, {"id": "113036838", "time_stamp": {"$date": 152