lots. You can tell this from the size of the logs generally harvested for firewood. It's not uncommon for people to destroy the unwanted smaller trees in order to pull out the big stuff.\nWith 'selective thinning' you'll see stretch marks on the remaining trees after only a few years - as growth accelerates, the canopy is opened up, and competition is removed. You hardly ever need to cut big healthy trees. Dead and dying trees are often dangerous to cut and are such a wonderful wildlife resource that they are best left. Intelligently harvested firewood consists mostly of smaller dia. trees. The best trees are grown on and individually harvested at maturity for fine furniture etc. Firewood should only be a small part of the overall harvest. Of course as you go back and rework an area (always with the same philosophy) the thinnings you harvest are inevitably of increased size. It's essentially just horticulture - on a larger scale. As we've only just begun to understand the symbiotic complexities of what's going on under the forest floor, whatever we do in terms of harvest should be done with a very high degree of humility. If you're not tearing up the forest with heavy machinery and ATV's it's almost impossible to see where you've been working after six months or so. After five or six years the growth on the remaining trees can be quite remarkable.\nA wood stove should only be considered as part of an equation. Buying and burning wood in a city, outside of that equation, makes absolutely no sense. English woodlands flourished for centuries while supporting a whole raft of different crafts. Trees were often selected decades in advance for particular uses and cultivated accordingly. Semi-industrialised mass clear cutting for ship building and steel making was the death knell for many areas. Excepting that, local people, intimately familiar with their locality, knew pretty precisely just how much they could sustainably harvest. You never clear-cut an area. You go out of your way to preserve the ground cover. You never open up areas to erosion. You avoid the temptation to clean up too much. Brash piles make great temporary habitat for wildlife and seedlings.", "recommendation_count": "8", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113035467", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520098671000}, "author": "KeepShtum", "author_id": "3175271", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Watch in awe as the Tories silently realise biomass at Drax was a huge and costly mistake and then attempt to 'relax' emissions regulations.", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "112946497", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1519952289000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Trees are part of short term carbon cycles so burning them is not as disruptive to long term carbon cycles as the burning of fossil fuels.\nWe're burning fossil fuels one million times faster than nature replenishes them which is warming the planet dangerously fast.\nBut burning trees doesn't help, for example Northern Boreal forest wildfires, which have been increasing due to increased heat, drought, pests and reduced snow cover, have been dumping ash on the Greenland Ice Sheet, increasing heat retention and melt rate.\nAnd the burning of the Amazon to make way for human activity is disrupting atmospheric rivers of moisture heading to mega-cities like Sao Paulo.\nIf the Amazon goes up in smoke, as one paper I read about suggested was a possibility at a temperature of 3 degrees C above pre-industrial, it could release enough carbon to push us well into a 4 degree world.", "recommendation_count": "14", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "increased heat drought", "effect": "which have been increasing"}]}, {"id": "113032889", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520093877000}, "author": "GKB507", "author_id": "11145063", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Part of the tragedy of the Canadian ta