 indeed expect ocean heat content to be high during a period of high solar/low volcanic activity, as both of these forcings lead to increased incident radiation on the oceans and hence a direct warming effect. Greenhouse forcing, however, does not exert a direct warming effect on the oceans. The huge bulk of the oceans, their depth, their slow rate of turnover and the high specific heat capacity of water all taken together mean that it will be many decades (or even centuries) before the oceans fully respond to the current warming.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "113416686", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "both of these forcings", "effect": "increased incident radiation on the oceans and hence a direct warming effect"}]}, {"id": "113417846", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520850788000}, "author": "TTauriStellarbody", "author_id": "16773618", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Yawn.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113401308", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113416686", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520849509000}, "author": "BuzzBloodOhio space", "author_id": "17722198", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"The present warming started well over a century ago but from a relatively cold baseline and there's no doubt that some of the early warming was due to a recovery in solar activity. In practice, it is only in recent decades that the warmth has become anomalous in the context of the Holocene as a whole. This period is characterised by pretty well the entire Earth warming at the same time - a synchronous, rapid and almost universal (except for parts of Antarctica) warming event that is very different in character to that the Earth experienced in medieval times.\"\nWell yes, thats what the balance of evidence seems to suggest, although - to argue synchronous or not requires a strict definition of what synchronous is - and more importantly, why that definition of synchronousity is important and arguably ho