ame or similar laws.\nIt would be nice if people who do not know what they are talking about would refrain from commenting, until they have done some research and inquired into the subject area, to ensure their comment is relevant, factual, true, and adds something positive to the article they are commenting on.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "113309111", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it will determine how these laws will be applied in future courts all around australia", "effect": "hence no matter how this case is decided it will have impact"}]}, {"id": "113333908", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520650186000}, "author": "anthLC", "author_id": "14805867", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I understand land clearing left unchecked is bad for the environment. But I don't agree with a blanket ban on land clearing. We have sufficient national parks and native reserves. Land clearing is a legitimate tool of farming and there is sufficient regulations already. Remember this land is zoned for farming purposes so restricting how farmers can manage this land is unfair and unreasonable. Environmentalists should buy then land if they ant it returned to native forests.\nLastly this article is written from a privilege UK viewpoint where hypocritically there is less native forest in existence or protected then currently is in Australia. So I feel the author should be looking at their own backyard first. Maybe start banning UK farmers clearing vegetation and insisting 30% of their land is returned to native forest. So that the UK percentage of forested land mass could rival Australia's.", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113333689", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520648652000}, "author": "anthLC", "author_id": "14805867", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "To explain it simply so you also can understand.\nPoint 1. It is there land they purchased it so yes they are entitled to use this land for farmin