ampaigns and policy at Choice. \u201cLab tests have also produced inconsistent results, which make realistic comparisons nearly impossible. It\u2019s time Australia follows the lead of other jurisdictions, such as the EU, and adopt real-world driving tests for emissions.\u201d\nVolkswagen became embroiled in a major corporate scandal \u2013 known as \u201cdieselgate\u201d \u2013 in 2015 when it emerged that millions of cars had been fitted with software designed to suppress emissions during testing. Almost 100,000 Australians own a car affected by the \u201cdefeat device\u201d software.\nA class action against Volkswagen on behalf of Australian owners is being heard in the federal court in Sydney. \nAs the federal government prepares to release new vehicle emissions standards, the AAA has argued there is no point setting tougher standards \u201cunless information on real-world performance is in the hands of consumers\u201d.\nVolkswagen has rejected the AAA\u2019s findings on the fuel efficiency of its recalled cars. \n\u201cThe German government approved Volkswagen\u2019s software update on the basis that it did not adversely affect the emissions or fuel economy of vehicles in test conditions,\u201d the company said in a statement. \u201cThe leading motorists\u2019 organisations in Germany, Austria and Switzerland have tested vehicles and concluded that vehicles continue to perform as expected after the software update.\u201d", "keyword_urls": ["https://www.theguardian.com/business/automotive-industry", "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/carbon-emissions", "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/air-pollution", "https://www.theguardian.com/money/consumer-affairs", "https://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-change", "https://www.theguardian.com/technology/motoring", "https://www.theguardian.com/tone/news"], "share_count": "0", "description": "Australian Automobile Association calls for real-world testing after finding nitrogen oxide emissions four times 