 large volume of non-greenhouse gases that have no effect at all on CO2's radiative properties.\nFurthermore, the increase has been entirely due to human activity. If industrialisation had not happened, CO2 would still be at the pre-industrial level of ~280 ppm.\nIt is correct to say that about one twentieth of all CO2 emissions are due to human activity (actually a bit less) but, again, that is something quite different. Natural CO2 emissions are fully offset by natural absorption, whereas anthropogenic emissions are only partly absorbed. The resulting imbalance may seem relatively small, but it accumulates over years and decades to produce a large CO2 rise.", "recommendation_count": "7", "in_reply_to": "113460341", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "mankind bqend", "effect": "that about a twentieth of that 0.01 % increase is"}, {"cause": "it relates co2 to something entirely irrelevant", "effect": "it makes little sense to express the co2 rise in percentage points"}, {"cause": "human activity", "effect": "furthermore the increase has been"}, {"cause": "human activity actually a bit less", "effect": "that about one twentieth of all co2 emissions are"}]}, {"id": "113466458", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1520935399000}, "author": "S_Charles", "author_id": "18050501", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The hand wringing is all too late. Enjoy the planet and its marvels while you can.The human race and the planet are doomed. We have reached a tipping point and even if we could find enough people with the power and will actually do something I don't think it would be enough. The human race is a destructive and self centred species both individually and collectively. The history of humans acting against their actual good rather than their vested interests is long. It is who we are.Carl Sagan in his comments on the blue dot summed up the context in which we should have been operating but instead we have operating in a context of ego and narrow petty interest