 ignite, which is why they are not used for thermal or metallurgical applications. Anthracite forms when bituminous coal undergoes low grade metamorphism which removal of the hydrocarbons which make the coal bituminous. Magmatic removal of volatile hydrocarbons is described in Ogden and Sleep.\n\"However that brings up their second mistake: low rank coals don't pass through a viscous phase when they are heated in the absence of oxygen (like some bitumenous coals do in a coke oven).\" \nThat suggests their contribution to the coal / magma mix would be to reduce its viscosity and facilitate its transport through sills, dykes and pipes toward the surface.", "recommendation_count": "12", "in_reply_to": "113657243", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the heat of the intrusion", "effect": "sharp and irregular variation in the yield of volatile substances and elementary composition"}]}, {"id": "113657505", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521251868000}, "author": "Klapper", "author_id": "3638543", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nOgden and Sleep don't suggest that \"every seam underlying 11,000 sq km out of 500,000 sq km totaling 92 m in cumulative thickness\"\nBQEND\nThen why do they calculate a number based on 92 m then?\nBQSTART\n but also described the situation of lesser cumulative thickness such as 30 m\nBQEND\nThat statement is incorrect. What they actually said was:\nBQSTART\n\"A typical moderately thick coal bed of 20\u201330 m (19) may be more realistic\"\nBQEND\nThey aren't talking about a cumulative 30 m of coal they're talking about \"a bed\". Anyway, they're wrong again since 30 m is not a \"moderately\" thick single seam, it's a seam of unusual thickness (for one seam).\nThere's no evidence this massive 1.5 trillion tonne mobilization of coal from depth to surface occurred by any means. Sure some coal came up the pipes, it had to, but coal flowing long distances underground (opposite to the flow of the basalt into the sill) is not a pla