}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"As to whether it explains how 1,000 cubic km of coal could be ejected to the surface, either by explosion as some scientists claim, or mixing with lava and being 'washed' to the surface\"\nProvide a reference to the peer reviewed papers published in proper scientific journals where some scientists claim that the coal was ejected the short distance to the surface by explosions. Note that explosive eruptions and incorporation of the coal into magma both occurred as described by Ogden and Sleep.\nIncorporation of surrounding bedrock by magma is a well researched feature of volcanism in part because it produces mineral deposits of economic value. In the early stages of a flood basalt event before feeder dykes become well coated with solidified magma incorporation by melting and fracturing of bedrock would be expected to occur. This was the case with the Siberian flood basalt province when eruptions started at the end of the Permian.\n\"neither one explains how every single seam underlying 11,000 sq km, and totaling 92 m in cumulative thickness could be incorporated and 'washed' to the surface.\"\nOgden and Sleep don't suggest that \"every seam underlying 11,000 sq km out of 500,000 sq km totaling 92 m in cumulative thickness\" was incorporated in rising magma and transported (\"washed\") to the surface but they do mention evidence in the region of magmatic intrusion into very small coal seams which is not surprising given the age and friability of the coal deposits. They also describe the heat liquification of coal by magmatic intrusion and consequent bouyancy driven movement of this coal magma mix up to the surface through joints typical of such sediments.\n\"It not plausible because there is not a cumulative 92 m of coal continuous across the basin.\"\nOgden and Sleep did not posit the need for a continuous cumulative 92 m of coal across the basin but also described the situation of lesser cumulative thickness such as 30 m and the need for a increase in the area subject to magmatic intrusion to around 40,000 sq km. 11,000 sq km or 40,000 sq km out of 500,000 sq km are both likely. Read the paper you linked to again to realise that the small areal extent was only one of the possibilities described by Ogden and Sleep.", "recommendation_count": "11", "in_reply_to": "113636469", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it produces mineral deposits of economic value", "effect": "incorporation of surrounding bedrock by magma is a well researched feature of volcanism in part"}]}, {"id": "113652791", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521238216000}, "author": "AvMichelCroz", "author_id": "13022945", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "I note with amusement that you have lost interest in discussing the Club of Rome. \nNo surprise.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "113626211", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113652727", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521238069000}, "author": "AvMichelCroz", "author_id": "13022945", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\u201cConfirmation bias, also called confirmatory bias or myside bias, is the tendency to search for, interpret, favor, and recall information in a way that confirms one's preexisting beliefs or hypotheses. It is a type of cognitive bias and a systematic error of inductive reasoning.\u201d\nIt\u2019s an error. \nYou like dressing things up by using different labels to try to make them seem different. Don\u2019t you realise that others are less superficial than you?", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113626211", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113652705", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521238019000}, "author": "Klapper", "author_id": "3638543", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nOnce heated to a few 100\u00b0C, the coal became viscous and released volatiles through a process analogous to industrial coke production.