in a 92 m thick seam. Do you think that there is an 11,000 sq km crater somewhere in Siberia?\"\nKeep in mind that the paper by Ogden and Sleep that you have quoted from describes on page 61 eruption from a small vent of the coal / magma mixture drawn from an area 1 km wide surrounding the vent. Such an eruption would last only 14 days as the coal/ magma mix is soon depleted. The intrusion of magma would work its way through the coal seams producing further vents and small eruptions. While these small vent eruptions would be explosive any craters created would be small and would have been buried by the non-intrusive Triassic basalts that followed.\nWhile craters or more correctly calderas 11,000 sq km in size are formed in island arc volcanism - for example Lake Toba, the mafic intrusion of coal seam volcanism produces instead a series of short lived small vents and small craters.\n\"1000 cubic km is approximately 1.5 trillion tons of coal-in-situ, but many orders of magnitude of interburden above the coal would need to have been 'exploded' to surface.\"\nAt the time of the mafic intrusions the Siberian coal measures would have been relatively young with at most only 60 millions years of overburden above them - its thickness dependent on the erosion and depositional history that followed its deposition. As described on page 60 of Ogden and Sleep, The overburden and the interburden (between the coal seams) did not need to be blown or exploded off as mafic magma intrusion liguified the coal causing it to move upward through joints to vents where explosive eruptions did occur. They describe magmatic intrusion and liquification of quite small coal seams as well as larger ones.\n\"It's not a reasonable argument that this much coal somehow was 'exploded' to the surface, along with all the rock interburden.\"\nNo one is making that argument. See paragraph above.\n\"I note my initial point that large quantities of coal cannot be burned underground as implied by this article