 other tropical rainforests) were the \u201clungs of the Earth\u201d, or similarly emotive nonsense - sorry I have limited patience for Biology when it indulges in philosophical narrative and strays away from science. Subsequently, as fashions changed, savannah and temperate grasslands were considered to be more important, as were the tremendous soil-creating capacity of temperate forests.\nIf we maintain the diversity, but manage agriculture so as to protect and enhance the thin soils, it may be that a better overall outcome could be achieved than simply leaving the rainforest to its own devices.\nAs an aside, it appears that there may be a perhaps 20,000 year cycle of greening and desertification of the Sahara. I wonder if South America is subject to a similar pattern, or if the Amazon rainforest is a relatively permanent feature of the current layout of continents.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113733808", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "partly the soil is thin and would require enormous inputs", "effect": "the key value of the great rainforests is the biodiversity they support"}]}, {"id": "113668174", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521288370000}, "author": "James Holland", "author_id": "18387395", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "So in practice, largely nuclear. I will read MacKay's document- it's just interesting to know people's position.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "113667496", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113667677", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521287406000}, "author": "AvMichelCroz", "author_id": "13022945", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\u201care you suggesting this makes it reasonable to cut it down now?\u201d\nNothing should be sacrosanct. Clearly a lot of people lived in the Amazon in areas now given over to forest. And the world did not end. Clearly paradigms other than \u201cabsolutely don\u2019t touch\u201d are possible.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "113666993", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113739782", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521456736000}, "author": "EthanolEurope", "author_id": "100074623", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Dr. Field posits a dichotomy between corn ethanol and switchgrass ethanol. This dichotomy is based on a supposed difference between the two that appears from application of a life cycle analysis. No doubt, Dr. Field has run such an analysis based on data that he has collected somehow and from someplace.\nWe (i) run the largest ethanol plant in Europe, processing corn, and (ii) we tried to build the largest cellulosic ethanol plant in the world, in Macedonia, running on switchgrass grown on marginal abandoned land (which we actually did- and it's still there in Macedonia if anyone wants to look at it). We are, as far as we know, the only people on the planet who could bridge Dr. Field's theory with actual data. We don't know Dr. Field. He has never contacted us. His work is certainly for us in no way informative; it is not even informed.\nTo our surprise, when we ran the numbers based on how things work in the real world, our corn ethanol has 80% GHG savings. Our switchgrass ethanol would have had 60-70% GHG savings. That was not the only reason that project was never built, but this is an important lesson. Lest anyone cheekily claim that our LCA doesn't include fertiliser or transport or anything else, this is a full LCA, not biased one way or another, with lots an lots of actual inputs instead of default values. It is what is required by law of any biofuel in the European Union.\nOut of touch academics like Dr. Field, who collect data only through desk research and who know so little about what that data represents (how people actually farm, how much natural gas is actually used, what conversion rations are practicable vs. what is promoted) do no service to climate research, and they often impede actual climate progress.\nBiofuels are needed to displace oil. Any biofuel that is better than oil deserves support. The academic fervour to identify the \"best biofuel\" is misguided both because we need lots of things to displace oil, not just one, and because academics are certain to get it wrong in identifying what is best (until they start getting mud on their shoes rather than simply scrolling the Internet).\nDr. Field's 2009 article was dead wrong because it used absurd data. Rather than search for better data, Field is not engaged in even more abstract theorising. That's not what this debate needs, Theory needs to be based on actual data.", "recommendation_count": "0", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "we need lots of things to displace oil and because academics are certain to get it wrong in identifying what is best", "effect": "the academic fervour to identify the biofuel is misguided both"}, {"cause": "academics are certain to get it wrong in identifying what is best", "effect": "because we need lots of things to displace oil and"}, {"cause": "it used absurd data", "effect": "dr. field 's 2009 article was dead wrong"}]}, {"id": "113667496", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521287088000}, "author": "AvMichelCroz", "author_id": "13022945", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Hydro where feasible. Nuclear where not feasible. Wind and solar in niche applications - in particular coupled with hydro. Potentially some natural gas. Local conditions may favour some storage. Possible Bly batteries in case pumped hydro not available. \nI suggest you should read the David MacKay document I referred to. It sets out a range of alternative approaches, including discussing the pros and cons. Why rely on my personal bias?", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "113666757", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113667415", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521286952000}, "author": "JulesBywaterLees", "author_id": "4738374", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "who says that?VW and the other automakers lobbied th