ipes work a lot better with no problems regarding an increased pressure within the pipe, and various issues. So if a country cannot or does not want to go 100% hydrogen, then combining biogas with hydrogen can both make up a significant proportion of domestic gas use with zero change to appliances or pipes. This is because biogas contains carbon dioxide and carbon monoxide which are easy to combine with hydrogen via biomethanation; producing a chemically-identical gas to the one we use today in most homes. Of overall domestic gas use in most western countries (without including transport of industry), this biogas could replace over 1/3 of domestic consumption; and in combination with H2 about two-thirds. With fuel cells or higher efficiency; lower demand, the figure is close to 100% - this is why many studies point to this being a viable and cost-effective route for gas companies to take going out to 2050. Personally, I believe hydrogen will play a more prominant role but certainly biogas is very much a growth industry and carries many other advantages for agriculture that cannot be avoided if we are to cope with these various problems concurrently.\nBiogas is in this way almost the opposite of biofuels.", "recommendation_count": "1", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it can be cheaper than refitting a very old metal gas network or some appliances waiting", "effect": "this is"}, {"cause": "biogas contains carbon dioxide and carbon monoxide which are easy to combine with hydrogen via biomethanation producing a chemically identical gas", "effect": "this is"}]}, {"id": "113693827", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521355870000}, "author": "AvMichelCroz", "author_id": "13022945", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\u201cAnd this seems to go against your defence of the status quo regarding heather-covered uplands, doesn't it?\u201d\nSorry - I don\u2019t see that. We already have demonstrably worse flooding in areas of the UK where catchments have had old grow