the sea bed is sinking under the increased weight of water above it"}]}, {"id": "113777302", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521512500000}, "author": "Walsunda", "author_id": "12483673", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"The advance and retreat of glaciers is a natural cycle that takes places over centuries.\"\nOver the last 2.6 million years largest scale advances and retreats of glaciers (glacial and interglacial periods) have occurred over 10,000s of years in response to orbital and axial oscillations or cycles. The last such major retreat occurrred between 19,000 and 9,000 years ago in response to a Northern Hemisphere high latitude summer insolation (NHHLSI) peak which provoked the oxidation of carbon rich ocean sediments in the Southern Ocean causing global greenhouse warming. Natural processes are defined as those independent of human agency. As there was no human agency in the oxidation of those Southern Ocean sediments, the global greenhouse warming from 19,000 to 9,000 years ago was natural.\nThis natural deglacial warming resulted in a world at 9,000 ybp warmer than preindustrial centuries of the last millennium. This world stayed warm for another 4,000 years, then temperatures declined as NHHLSI declined resulting in the expansion of glaciers in recent millennia up until last century.\nThe very rapid warming and consequent current retreat of glaciers is caused by CO2 from the oxidation of coal and other fossil fuels by combustion which has involved human agency and is therefore not natural.\nMany glaciers in retreat have revealed tree stumps of earlier forestation, screeds\" (screes) \"where they terminated in earlier times, and in a few cases human settlements\".\nThe human settlements reflect the warmer times particularly before around 5,000 ybp as do the terminal and higher lateral moraine screes and evidence of a higher tree line.\n\"Sea level is not rising any faster than it was before according to tidal gauges.\"\nSea level was stable from 200 BC to 1000 AD, then rose at an average rate of 0.6 mm per year up to 1400 AD. It was stable again from 1400 AD to the late 19th century since then rose 210 mm from 1880 to 2009.\nSee Church and White (2011) \"Sea Level Rise from the Late 19th to Early 21st Century\" Surveys in Geophysics Volume 32 Issue 4-5 pp 585-602 September.\nNote Figure 5 which shows the global mean sea level rise from the late 19th century to 2009.\nThe authors conclude as follows.\n\"The linear trend from 1900 to 2009 is 1.7 + or - 0.2 mm per year and since 1961 1.9 + or - 0.4 mm per year. There is considerable variability in the rate of rise during the twentieth century but there has been a statistically significant acceleration since 1880 and 1900 of 0.009 + or - 0.003 mm per year per year and 0.009 + or - 0.004 mm per year per year respectively.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "113752457", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "global greenhouse warming"}, {"cause": "this natural deglacial warming", "effect": "a world"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "the expansion of glaciers"}, {"cause": "co2", "effect": "the very rapid warming and consequent current retreat of glaciers"}]}, {"id": "113777187", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521512110000}, "author": "xwookey", "author_id": "4307215", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nIs that not an option?\nBQEND\nOf course it's an option, but many people struggle with the idea that things can (and should/must) change.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113773824", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113776886", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521510944000}, "author": "timallard", "author_id": "11998852", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Controlling heat and freshwater from entering the Arctic Ocean with levees to prevent early melt away from shorelines and create a global \"cold forcing\" by with sea ice polders and methods to refreeze methane plumes: https://forum.ar