ears up to about 50 years ago. Or, if we're very lucky, only 20 years ago.\nBut over the last 50 years and certainly over the last 20 years emissions haven't crashed to barely anything. They're risen inexorably over the timeframe. \nSo, if the record temperatures we've seen are as a response to historic emissions and not to what we've put into the atmosphere over the last few decades, and if as a result of those historic emissions the arctic is mush, we're seeing sea levels rising, the seas are acidified, there is increased flooding, huge increase in drought and wildfire, appalling bleaching of coral reefs and ever more catastrophic hurricanes - but that's all without what we've put into the atmosphere over the last few decades, what kind of state do you think the climate will be in in 50 years' time? Given the feedback systems? \n(Feedback systems being one thing that triggers another, as in, as the oceans warm, metahne is released from the deep seat bed, which createws further warming, which releases more methane, in a cycle which gradually intensified and speeds up.And there are many others.\nA few years ago in India temperatures rose so high (over 40C degrees) that people could not touch surfaces without blistering their hands. You took so calmly about 'adaption', 'coping', 'resilience'. But what about when temperatures reach 50C in India - ? The population won't survive that. Higher still and people will boil alive if they go outside.\nThese temperature rises are not survivable. \nThe mistake you're making, as so many do, is to imagine that global warming is linear and will increase ever so gradually and gently over several decades. That gradually the temperatures will rise, like a barometer in the summer as the day advances in to the afternoon from the cooler morning. That is slightly what is happening now, today, NOW. But when the trigger points are reached, and warming goes out of control, and the exponential effect kicks in, temperatures will soar. Very very fast. Who knows how fast? If you think back to Sunday, when temperatures were minus 0 across the country, but by the next day were several degrees warmer - who's to say that a rise from 40C to 50C to 60C or higher won't happen almost overnight? I hope it doesn't, but who's to say it won't?\nWhich leaves me very frightened. Not 'pessimistic' - just bloody terrified. You, not so much. So - reach the literature, listen to talks, watch the slides, understand the science. \nThen try to work with others to get politicians to act.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113823140", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113833179", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521634511000}, "author": "ClareLondon", "author_id": "1372819", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nI don't share this particular aspect of your pessimism.\nBQEND\nBut you're completely missing the point. You're shutting down the science and instead defaulting to talking about my emotional state. As if it's all down to my pessimism rather than the science. Putting it down to 'pessimism' is neither here nor there. Out of control global warming will take place at certain trigger points regardless of whether I'm 'pessimistic', 'happy', 'angry', 'miserable', 'deliriously happy' or any other emotional state I might happen to be in.  \nBQSTART\nI do believe that we humans are in for a terrible time collectively, and a great deal of innocent flora and fauna will be collateral damage. But I have worked for 35 years in IT related industries\nBQEND\nBut, begging your pardon, this is ridiculous. You can't compare the cliamte system and atmosphere to your knowledge of computers. I know about computers, too. I have written software in the past, too. What's know about system design in computers got to do with it? I could talk about my intricate knowledge of the m mechanics of vacuum clceaners, or jet engines, or suspension bridges and it still won't have a damned thing to do with the climate system. 