prevalent. I then pointed out that water vapour does not \"contribute to climate change\" which is why I left it out of the list of contributory causes.\nPut in scientific terms, I'm talking about forcings - sources of energy that induce change. Increases in atmospheric greenhouse gases like CO2 and methane trap additional energy in the environment. Water vapour does not - there can be no increase in water vapour in advance of temperature rises, only afterwards. Water vapour is uneven in distribution, unlike CO2e gases; cold places are very dry, hot places very humid, and neither effect can be considered 'global'.\nWater vapour also cannot be described as anthropogenic; we do not emit, directly cause or increase water vapour (except in very small local events like power station cooling towers). \nSo - CO2, methane et. al. cause global warming. Water vapour doesn't, but it does play a major part in retaining the heat once it's in the atmosphere or oceans.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "113814979", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "al", "effect": "global warming"}]}, {"id": "113822734", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521619735000}, "author": "BillSoko", "author_id": "18386839", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "there are some who deny everything including their own existence ........ evolution of H sapiens has not been very even.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113811865", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113822508", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521619129000}, "author": "BillSoko", "author_id": "18386839", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "yep, another opportunity to 'capitalize' on ..... don't stress; WE will now fix the problem we caused but YOU went along with ... well, were paid you to come for the ride... DON'T try to tell US how to fix the problem.... didn't you and your kids watch Mickey Mouse..?", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113795285", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "we", "eff