 it is now is mud, and the area of the ocean floor that has been transformed from forest to level mud, to parking lot, is equivalent to the entire area of all the forests that have ever been cut down on all of the earth in the history of humanity. \nWe've managed to do that in the last 100 to 150 years.\u201d\nhttps://www.ted.com/talks/jeremy_jackson/transcript", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "113780697", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it clears it away", "effect": "think of it as being kind of the bulldozing of a city or of a forest"}]}, {"id": "113800647", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521559252000}, "author": "R Anon", "author_id": "17206208", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Good to see you are back on form & thanks for the links.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "113795234", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113795440", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521551930000}, "author": "ClareLondon", "author_id": "1372819", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "What puzzles me, I simply can't wrap my brain around it, is why lies are perpetuated everywhere. Here, in the Guardian, there is article after article quoting someone saying that emissions must be reduced, brought under control, by this date or that.\nBut, the latency in the system means the atmosphere hasn't even responded yet to emissions from decades ago. It makes no sense to pretend that stopping NOW will do a damned thing. It won't.\nI was thinking about this recently, trying to work my way painfully to an answer. One option - ignorance. Politicians don't know. But, they have had so many briefings, scientists have given talks, with data, with slides, with presentations, at Westminster and elsewhere for literally decades, explaining carefully how the science works. So they can't not know - can they?\nAnd yet, a few months ago I was at an event and met my local MP and mentioned this latency problem and she stared at me and said, oh, really, I didn't know that, is that so? As if she'd never heard of it. As if she too believed that if everyone within the borough 'cut back' today that would be a contributing to 'halting climate change'.\nSo then I thought, OK, they do all know, or most of them know, but they're all specialists in different fields, as politicians, they all have their briefs, so they simply put the information into a different compartment in theirminds, file it away, think it's for other people to deal with. Yet, the vast majority of politicains will have partners, families, children - and they're not shit scared?\nI'm demented with fear and I don't even have kids.\nI'm so long past the terrible grief of climate change. There was a time when I couldn't cope. When I thought of what the world will lose. Not just people, not just scientific knowledge, not just the natural world, but the inspiration of great minds, great composers, writers, architects, philosophers, dancers, artists, photographers, thinkers, entertainers. I find the thought of all human progress being chucked away deeply distressing.\nNow, I don't shrug, far from it, but I've practised for a very long time now acceptance, or, more accurately, resignation. Nothing is being done, properly, businesses are still pouring noxious fumes into the air, emissions are pretty much the same, and for decades despite knowledge of what was going on hardly anything has been done and what there is is vastly too little vastly too late. It's obvious there is no hope. We are in a planetary emergency, there will be a mass wipeout of life on earth and give the timeframe of the emissions and the rapid warming, the earth will probably end up as a ball of fire in the sky, as Stephen Hawkings said. I think he's right. Earth will become another Venus.\nSo - and I've asked this question again and again - how is it that given the reality of the science, that this newspaper, which is not a stupid paper, and others, cheerfully allow articles to be published referring to 'in 50 years' time' and talk about the impact of cuts in X decades time, or this generation ofyoung people 'when they retire' - or anything at all, as if the world is going to continue as it is?\nIs it lack of knowledge? - surely not. Is it that while the planet heats up people are just inclined to look after their own interests, make their money, create their product (this newspaper), shutting their eyes to reality?\nOr is it this. Is it that the 'don't frighten the horses' approach to the reality of climate change and the impending apocalypse is very political indeed; it's simply a case of those who could inform the public, deliberately not informing the public, so as to keep the hysteria and terror at bay, so as to maintain public order.\nBecause, frankly, if people really understood, wouldn't there be protests around the world every day of the week, every hour, people standing in groups shouting and calling out for action? And, had people known, properly, wouldn't there have been such protests for at least the last 20 years? I think there would have been. \nBut, fact, the truth is not acknowledged, the public is not told and the BBC still drags out its climate deniers for 'balance' and Nigel Lawson still comes out with his crap and there is no court action forcing misinformation to be illegal.\nI think the lack of honest reporting on what is about to happen must be public order control. Mustn't it? I can't think of another single reason why so many hundreds of politicians barely mention global warming, as if they are unaware the arctic is mush, temperatures are escalating and we're on the edge of very savage times.", "recommendation_count": "8", "in_reply_to": "113783961", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113795285", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521551741000}, "author": "Lawrie Griffith", "author_id": "13793892", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Now this is not my view. But it is useful to be aware of how some others think.\nThere is another way in which the problem is seen. Especially by business people.Managerialism.Briefly, it goes something like this:\nGlobal warming is real. But the effects are not acute yet. We can't crash the economy in a panicked response. That would make things worse and hurt very large numbers of people.As the problem develops, technological solutions will emerge.Demand for products and services that fix the problem will emerge.The market will meet that demand.Governmental policy will shift to facilitate effective responses.Resources will be adjusted to support this.This will direct science and technology to deliver the necessary technological fixes.There is sufficient know how and flexibility in the system to solve the problem over a realistic timescale.\nIt is seen as a management problem, and will therefore be put right as one part of the greater human enterprise. (US style).Rex Tillerson, ex secretary of state, ex oil executive, is a strong advocate of this position.\nYou and I might not agree. But knowing what the big end of town are thinking is helpful in understanding the casualness of the response to climate change by the corporate sector.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "113792872", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113800539", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521559086000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\u201c'One of the frustrations of dealing with this issue is that it is virtually beyond the grasp of human imagination.\u201c\nIt is difficult to imagine that our shoreline, which was relatively stable for thousands of years, is beginning to move inland.\nHard to wrap one\u2019s mind around the loss of our great coastal cities with their history, art and culture.", "recommendation_count": "8", "in_reply_to": "113795234", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113799196", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521557079000}, "author": "rockyrex", "author_id": "2923581", "schema_org_type": "http: