 or are well underway. \nBQSTART\nPotential effects on climate in the 21st century include the creation of drought-prone regions in North America and central Asia as part of a shifting of climatic zones, erosion of the West Antarctic ice sheet with a consequent worldwide rise in sea level, and opening of the fabled Northwest Passage.\nBQEND\nAnd from a New Yorker article by the Pulitzer-Prize winning author Elizabeth Kolbert about James Hansen:\nBQSTART\nFrom early on, the significance of Hansen\u2019s insights was recognized by the scientific community. \u201cThe work that he did in the seventies, eighties, and nineties was absolutely groundbreaking,\u201d Spencer Weart, a physicist turned historian who has studied the efforts to understand climate change, told me. He added, \u201cIt does help to be right.\u201d \n\u201cI have a whole folder in my drawer labelled \u2018Canonical Papers, \u2019 Michael Oppenheimer, a climate scientist at Princeton, said. \u201cAbout half of them are Jim\u2019s.\u201d\nBQEND\nhttp://www.nytimes.com/1981/08/22/us/study-finds-warming-trend-that-could-raise-sea-levels.html\nhttp://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/06/29/the-catastrophist", "recommendation_count": "31", "in_reply_to": "113779693", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113783091", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521535025000}, "author": "UnsightlyOdour", "author_id": "17316048", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "When there\u2019s no food left people like you will be the first to be eaten", "recommendation_count": "6", "in_reply_to": "113782643", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113779693", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521523386000}, "author": "Erik Frederiksen", "author_id": "15131989", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The Earth has a great deal of carbon it can give up as the world warms, how fast is the question.From a 2012 TED Talk by NASA's former lead climate scientist.\nBQSTART\nSo CO2, methane, and ice sheets were feedbacks that amplified global temperature change causing these ancient climate oscillations to be huge, even though the climate change was initiated by a very weak forcing. \nThe important point is that these same amplifying feedbacks will occur today. The physics does not change. As Earth warms, now because of extra CO2 we put in the atmosphere, ice will melt, and CO2 and methane will be released by warming ocean and melting permafrost. \nWhile we can't say exactly how fast these amplifying feedbacks will occur, it is certain they will occur, unless we stop the warming. There is evidence that feedbacks are already beginning.\nPrecise measurements by GRACE, the gravity satellite, reveal that both Greenland and Antarctica are now losing mass, several hundred cubic kilometers per year. And the rate has accelerated since the measurements began nine years ago. Methane is also beginning to escape from the permafrost.\nWhat sea level rise can we look forward to? The last time CO2 was 390 ppm, today's value, sea level was higher by at least 15 meters, 50 feet. Where you are sitting now would be under water. Most estimates are that, this century, we will get at least one meter. I think it will be more if we keep burning fossil fuels, perhaps even five meters, which is 18 feet, this century or shortly thereafter.\nBQEND\n\nhttps://www.ted.com/talks/james_hansen_why_i_must_speak_out_about_climate_change/transcript", "recommendation_count": "49", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "extra co2", "effect": "as earth warms we put in the atmosphere"}]}, {"id": "113783047", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521534938000}, "author": "twitgit", "author_id": "16045352", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "We (UK) have a Minister (Clark, BEIS) with responsibilty for climate change policy within his brief. But when did you last hear him speak on this? I don't think he gets the urgency of the situation - too busy with Brexit.", "recommendation_count": "12", "in_reply_to": "113782715", "causal_rel