s over the years and decades, and it demonstrates how deceitful Nuccitelli is being. The actual denial is not of if, but of how much global warming is likely to occur from our accelerating CO2 emissions and its increasing concentration from 280 ppm 150 years ago to 405 ppm now, on its way to a double of 560 ppm later this century. The how much is a function of two things-1) quantity of CO2 emissions2) climate sensitivity to CO2- the amount of warming from a doubling of CO2 ppmThese two are critical factors for any understanding how much warming will occur- continued modest warming, which seems the most likely trend, and would probably be benign as Freeman Dyson, Richard Lindzen, and Bjorn Lombourg predict or serious, even catastrophic warming from high climate sensitivity, as James Hansen and a few others predict. \nFor over 50 years, determining climate sensitivity has been the main quest of climate science, but it stubbornly remains in the huge range of 1.5 to 4.5 according to the IPCC (and 0.6 to 6.0 if we include the outliers Lindzen and Hansen). The un-quantifiable positive and negative feed backs, mostly from from H20 water vapor and clouds, have so far made the determining climate sensitivity impossible. \nThe \"climate denial\" Nuccitelli characterizes as science denial is instead the well respected position that climate sensitivity is near the low end of the IPCC 1.5 to 4.5 range, based on the empirical record, global temperatures the past 20 years, and the majority of recent peer reviewed papers by climate scientists. \nWhereas, helping the public and politicians understand climate science so that we might find common ground and craft responsible policy for what is likely- a continuing warming trend (about 0.9 C degrees the past 150 years) and sea level rise (about 2-3 mm per year) Nuccitelli instead is a source of misrepresentation about climate change, climate consensus, climate denial, and climate science. If you count him as a friend of climate science