 completely different. Electric cars are becoming viable and people are slowly moving over to them. What they up against (or were) is decades of development and an incredibly well developed mass production techniques. Most cars with ICEs are ridiculously cheep for the amount of precision engineering in them. It's a tough nut to crack.\nThe other thing is the extensive network of petrol stations in every country, whereas public charging facilities are still very limited. That's why plug in hybrids are a great idea. That let people charge at home or when they can, but can still fill up with petrol if necessary. Eventually, I expect full electric to take over, but hybrids bridge the gap pretty well. Unless of course fuel cells take off in a big way.\nI don't know if there are good prospects for vast battery farms, like Tesla's. Maybe not for long storage to cover long periods of intermittency.\nGrid scale battery storage still has some advantages in helping to cover smaller gaps in the short term. Which means more spinning reserve can be taken out and used for supplemental reserve increasing overall efficiency of the system.\nOther options are being investigated too, such as molten salt storage and power to gas.\nNot everything will work. We should expect some , if not most of these pilots to fail. But we should keep going.\n20 years ago I thought biofuel would be far better than it has been, but I would have laughed at the idea of solar PV being anywhere near where it is today. It's not always easy to predict which technologies will work out, which is why all options need to be investigated.\nBQSTART\nIt's a sort of Turing Test. You post comments, and they reveal things about you. Simple.\nBQEND\nThe Turing test would only show I'm human. I'd hope you'd at least work that out.\nSounds more like Psychographic profiling. You don't work for Cambridge Analytica do you?\nAlright then, just for fun, let's see what you've got. I won't be offended and I'll be honest in lettin