osts continuing to escalate (with increasing public anger at getting caught coming and going, and the large scale manufacturing industries in the State have now all closed down - at least in part due to energy costs), the state government decides to install storage capacity. Not just any storage capacity, a lithium array supplied by Elon Musk. To say that this was expensive would be an understatement. The key factor was that it was supplied in the shortest period of time once Jay (the premier) and his mates had decided that it was time to swallow a spider to catch the fly they swallowed when they built such a huge wind array with no complementary developments to make it work properly. And the reason for the rush? An upcoming state election. Thus the immense successes of this new battery were constantly in the press until just about the time that the election was held and Jay and his mates lost. As of early 2018 Jay and his mates are out of power and the Liberals are in.\nOne expensive battery, of very limited capacity, was/is not the answer. And indeed the elements of that battery are going to need to be replaced starting in around 12 months or so, in order to remain on the most favourable part of the cost curve of capacity/function vs operating cost. I leave the interested reader to research this more deeply themselves, my purpose is not to debate the fact that storage batteries are essentially a consumable.\nThis battery is a somewhat superficial non-solution. I'm sure we will hear a lot more about it now that there has been a change of government. In addition, perhaps the review that was carried out on the effectiveness and economics of the wind installations, draft report buried without trace in 2013, will now see the light of day. One can only hope that some sort of objective review will result in a sensible energy policy and way forwards being decided upon and executed.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113960465", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "