 of colour) in an area flooded by sea level rise following global warming. CO2 was involved then as was the placement of continents and other land masses around Antarctica. Tectonic removal of one such land mass leading to the development of the circum-Antarctic current and a significant drop in atmospheric CO2 led to global cooling 70 million years later; and led with the assistance of cyclic variations in Southern Hemisphere high latitude summer insolation Antarctic to widespread continental glaciation on the great southern continent. Changes in Atlantic currents following the growth of the Isthmus of Panama and a decline from higher Pliocene CO2 levels led, in combination with variations in Northern Hemisphere high latitude summer insolation (NHHLSI), to the glacial and interglacial periods of the last 2.6 million years. Each deglacial warming that transitioned from glacial to interglacial over thousands of years while initiated by NHHLSI was largely carried out by CO2. So a wide ranging view of the evidence for the causes of global warming shows that CO2 often plays a major part.\nThis time NHHLSI is declining and no other likely suspects have panned out; but CO2 has increased by 40% since the 19th century. The evidence is there.", "recommendation_count": "5", "in_reply_to": "113993008", "causal_relations": [{"cause": null, "effect": "global"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "the development of the circum antarctic current and a significant drop in atmospheric co2 led to global cooling 70 million years later"}]}, {"id": "114045965", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522133254000}, "author": "Steve Jones", "author_id": "11108528", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Ok, I used to live in a place that required next to no space heating.Also lived in a Victorian terrace that required plenty in winter.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "114042477", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114045768", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522132587000}, "author": "Joh