en technology.\nSimilarly intermittent renewables complement (to a degree) gas which is a more dynamic supply.If we decided to remove it or not replace it then, like Germany we would be forced to remain using coal and gas for 'baseload' provision for an indeterminate period -possibly to 2050.\nAs Germany has discovered, you cannot simply swap a high availability dispatchable power source for an intermittent one.This isn't lawnmowers.\nBQSTART\nMeanwhile offshore wind say they are going to do it, and do it- I'm sure you would be the first to crow at any delay or budget over run.\nBQENDNo, because I support a MIX of renewables and nuclear.\nYou and Marty have this obsessive view on a 'battle' between renewables -vs- nuclear as if they're opposing football teams.It so misses the point.\nCould EDF overrun their schedule at HPC?Yes, it's entirely possible - and that would be a shame, just as much as if investment falls for renewables once the guaranteed subsidy tapers off.\nYou need to remember that the objective is to cut emissions.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "114019213", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "i support a mix of renewables and nuclear", "effect": "bqendno"}]}, {"id": "114021606", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522068823000}, "author": "SunRoad", "author_id": "18399512", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Total useful energy extracted from trees will never exceed the solar and planetary energy put into constructing them: a.k.a The Fifth Law.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "114018799", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114010156", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522056032000}, "author": "Steve Jones", "author_id": "11108528", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "AMC, I fear you are wasting your time trying to reason with JS. Everything is black or white and no nuance in between.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "114009473", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114010148", "time_stamp": {"