ombination of the fact that the market must be imperfect (because we can't know the true carbon price); and the fact that it is aiming to spend the least necessary to meet the goal; sounds to me like a high risk recipe for disaster.\nIn summary, it seems hard to design a market that works; and even if we did, the market would be trying to do as little as necessary, when we can never be truly sure how \"little\" that is.\nBQSTART\nAdapting and extending this principle could be highly successful in decarbonising the generation mix.....but it's not going to happen on its own (which I think was your point).\nBQEND\nI think other measure are far more important and effective.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "114166741", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the pricing mechanism is not designed properly", "effect": "now of course this could just be"}]}, {"id": "114219857", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522511076000}, "author": "loco_p_man", "author_id": "13126382", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Your quotation is from a study running from 2010 to 2013 in the US only. How shabbily dishonest of you.\nEven in the UK, solar can now be subsidy free :Clayhill \u2013 the UK\u2019s first subsidy-free solar farm\nThe Dutch have just contracted for their first subsidy-free wind farm : \"On Monday (19 March), the Dutch government announced that its call for tender for zero-subsidy offshore wind bids had paid off and that Vattenfall would build two facilities in the North Sea by 2022.\nAlthough the government has taken on certain risks like connecting the wind farms to the country\u2019s power grid, the successful tender means that the farms will sell the electricity they generate on the wholesale market rather than relying on revenue stabilisation schemes.\"", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "114218307", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114193624", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522420543000}, "author": "kent31", "author_id": "15456519", "schema_