ay the balance in tax to the govt. So far so good.\nThis pushes up the price of coal generation in the UK, so less coal is used an alternatives fill the gap. Great for the UK.\nBut the ETS covers Europe. The Uk coal generators can transfer permits to elsewhere in Europe, and the carbon is emitted there. That's the problem.\nBQSTART\nSo the conclusion should be that the ETS mechanism is poorly designed, not that better ones can't be built. \nBQEND\nTrue, and as a starting point it should cover the whole world. Which is why I'm saying it is a difficult thing to actually design and implement.\nBQSTART\nOf course the market will do as little as necessary. \nBQEND\nIt would be safer to do as much as possible, rather than as little as necessary. Especially when we cannot know how \"little\" is necessary.\nBQSTART\nAs for not knowing the \"true\" price of carbon, there's no such thing. \nBQEND\nYes there is. It just cannot be known. That is the entire problem. We can only guess at the price, because it depends upon the cost of future impacts. If we get that price wrong, then the market (doing the minimum necessary as it always does) may not do enough.\nBQSTART\n \nBQSTART\nI think other measures are far more important and effective. \nBQEND\nWhat would these be ?\nBQEND\nImposing mandatory goals, rather than waiting for the market to meander its way towards \"discovering\" them. Such as setting dates of phasing out fossil fuel technologies, banning exploration for new reserves, and setting maximum limits on emissions per kWh.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "114174228", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "it depends upon the cost of future impacts", "effect": "we can only guess at the price"}]}, {"id": "114174918", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522359864000}, "author": "loco_p_man", "author_id": "13126382", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\n\"Looking up\" is not enough, you need to read the data correctly.\nBQEND\nOh yes, that is most c