"3522873", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nRenewables coupled with storage will make coal redundant.\nBQEND\nWhat happens in a scenario where wind power runs at half or a third average for 2 weeks? Such a situation is common. You need about a week's electricity storage to make up the difference. \nIf you are expecting 25 GW of wind power, and get 12 GW average over 2 weeks, you need 4.4 TWH of storage to make up the difference. That's about 34,000 batteries the size of the one Tesla recently installed in South Australia. That battery costs somewhere between $50 million and $100 million. That works out at $1.7 - $3.4 trillion.\nYou could try to replace batteries with pumped hydro. That's much cheaper. Snowy 2 would add 350 GWH of storage, so you'd only need about 12.5 of those, at about $5 billion each. That's \"only\" $63 billion. But that assumes there are a dozen places you could build something the size of Snowy 2, and of course there aren't. You'd end up with a lot of smaller sites and the price would be much higher.\nThe cheapest site identified in the UK for a future large pumped hydro scheme is Coire Glas. That would provide 30 GWH for \u00a3800 million. Australia would need 147 of them, costing \u00a3118 billion.\nAnd then you'd face the problem of what happens if wind speeds remain low for 3 or 4 weeks instead of 2, which happens much less often, but still needs to be accounted for.\nThere isn't a single significantly sized country in the world running on a mix of intermittent renewables and storage. Even the places that have tried, like El Hierro in the Canary Islands, still rely on fossil fuel backup. Germany, for all the money it's spent building wind and solar, still relies on coal and lignite for firm power capacity.\nIf you look at the ACOLA report into a high renewables scenario for Australia it still relies on fossil fuel backup providing about 25% of supply over the year. You cannot replace reliable supply with systemically unreliable sources like wind and solar, because the cost of storage to make it work is prohibitive.\nSadly the thrust of the argument amongst renewable supporters, egged on by the anti-nuclear brigade like the Guardian, is to build wind and solar and wait until batteries become cheap enough before we get rid of coal and gas. But batteries aren't going to become cheap enough, and a mixed wind/solar/gas scenario results in emissions being far higher than required.\nIf you look at the countries of Europe, only 3 meet future emissions targets. Norway, which is almost entirely conventional dammed hydro, Sweden, which is a mix of conventional hydro and nuclear, and France, which is mainly nuclear. Germany, despite all the investment in intermittent renewables, has emissions roughly 10 times higher than France.\nThe choice is simple. To meet emissions targets you build a lot of nuclear power. That's the only technology that can currently get emissions low enough. Building wind and solar cannot, and will leave emissions 3 times higher than safe levels.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "114133815", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the cost of storage to make it work is prohibitive", "effect": "you can not replace reliable supply with systemically unreliable sources like wind and solar"}, {"cause": null, "effect": "emissions"}]}, {"id": "114142078", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522312848000}, "author": "ArtistFrmlyKnwnAs", "author_id": "16359247", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nthe question should really be about why successive governments have allowed 'gouging'?\nBQEND\nNo it shouldn't. You have presented no evidence that previous governments allowed gouging.\nNor did I mention governments at all. I stated simply that customers are not happy with being gouged by privatised suppliers. It isn't governments doing the billing.", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "114136431", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "1141370