.\nFirst, osmosis is not a heat transfer mechanism. \nThe currents in the oceans actually move very slow and there is no place where a large change will occur over such a short period such as the false analogy of pouring hot water into a tank. \nOcean temperatures change slowly due to the specific heat of water being very high. As a result, the number of temperature measurements over an area need not be very large\u2014actually much less than land measurements. The currents move slowly and weather buoys and other methods (such as ship intake data) actually sample large portions of the ocean to high accuracy. This is why place like the cold blob off Greenland can be accurately identified\u2026something you have indicated as not possible. \nThere is no better example how accurate temperature data is then the El Nino/La Nina oscillation. The standard for measuring temperature in that section of Pacific Ocean define the bands needed to identify the ocean temperatures for each phenomenon. See link\nhttps://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/teleconnections/enso/indicators/sst.php\nOcean temperature are measured with weather buoys\u2014for information: \nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weather_buoy\nPlus now, satellites can use passive IR/microwave to measure sea surface temps at very high temporal and special resolution\nhttp://www.remss.com/measurements/sea-surface-temperature/", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "114302231", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "the specific heat of water", "effect": "ocean temperatures change slowly"}]}, {"id": "114317438", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522772259000}, "author": "James Holland", "author_id": "18387395", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Just to repeat for the hard of thinking-\"Your position seems to be 'nothing need be done'.\"\"And now we are back to your other meme (sic) that nothing is being done..\"Perhaps English is not your first language, AV.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "114312842", "causal