 it will be funded/incentivised by a high carbon price.. Apparently it has to happen anyway, so in that sense that cost is not relevant. If there's no alternative, you just pay up.\n I also have to say that the privatisation of power generation in this country really does not seem to have been an outstanding success. The Queensland government had to intervene to stop its own subsidiary rorting the spot power market and driving prices sky high, and similar rorting was the reason the SA government wanted control of some of the output from the Hornsdale/Tesla battery. This rorting was perfectly legal under power market rules, and provided better returns for shareholders, but curtailing it was in the public interest even if it wasn't \"business-friendly\". Power is an essential service, and there are good arguments for not privatising essential services.\nAnyway, Jenkins' article says there is no real problem with up to 50% grid-scale wind+solar, even without storage. So, Labor's policy of 50% renewables by 2030 seems perfectly sound as a starting point, particularly when storage is added to the mix. On top of that we have an extra 7% from hydroelectricity (although there are some doubts as to its long term reliability under difficult rainfall patterns). I expect there will also be minor generation from geothermal and biogas (there is some already) so that should bring us close to 60% renewables.\nGiven that nuclear is not currently feasible in this country, for a variety of reasons, I think Labor's current policy is looking like an excellent place to start. If we need to re-assess things as 2030 gets closer then we (and Jenkins) can do that with the benefit of the better information that will be available by then.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "114241204", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "114234574", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1522568969000}, "author": "RossHosking", "author_id": "12104671", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "The po