yled US archeologist Ron Wyatt and US marine salvage operator David Fosold using a gadget advertised in treasure hunting magazines an ark shaped structure complete with metal nails on Mt Tendurek in eastern Turkey, 18 km south of Mt Ararat.\nIn 1985 after completing a survey of Cretaceous tetrapod fossil sites in Queensland, I commenced post graduate studies at the University of Queensland in paleontology and evolution. At the time Queensland was under an undemocratic extreme right wing regime and US creationists were providing hundreds of thousands of dollars per annum finance to local creationists to set up a base here. I went with my supervisor and Ian Lowe to a number of creationist talks to provide some scientific balance. Ian later became President of the Australian Conservation Foundation and an early communicator of the reality uncovered by climate science. \nIn 1988 David Fosold returned to Mt Tendurek accompanied by Australian geologist and concluded that the boat shaped structure was a natural geological phenomenon. Ian Pilmer had became a campaigner against creationists some time after me.\nIn the late noughties Ian Pilmer criticised the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change for being unscientific and was quoted by then Opposition Leader Tony Abbott to that effect. In 2010 he toured with Christopher Monkton as a support act in Australia.\nIn late 2010 I attended the Woodford Folk Festival with My daughter and her not yet one year old son where as Minister for Climate Change she was delivering a talk with Ian Lowe on climate change and global warming. While my duties were mainly toddler focused, I met Ian and reminded him of our encounters with creationists and he of course mentioned the similaries both in personnel, organisations and techniques of both groups. While Ian Pilmer may seem to be an exception to this pattern, he was a late adopter and a hard rock person.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "113865577", "causal_relations": null},