 a base year. The publishers of Science and Eurekalert (the AAAS) summarised the study's main findings as follows:\n\"Globally, according to the new data, the number of floods and other hydrological events have quadrupled since 1980 and have doubled since 2004, highlighting the urgency of adaptation to climate change. Climatological events, such as extreme temperatures, droughts, and forest fires, have more than doubled since 1980. Meteorological events, such as storms, have doubled since 1980 (Figure 1, 2013 (Figure 2.1 in 2013 report); Figure 2, 2018 (Figure 1 in 2018 updated publication).\" [AAAS 21.93.2018]\nThe main concern for Europe is whether the Gulf Stream is being affected by climate change. There seems to be broad agreement among the 27 EU agencies (EASAC = European Science Academies) that the AMOC is slowing but that a collapse of this crucial climatic determiner is unlikely.", "recommendation_count": "3", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113866383", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521711006000}, "author": "James Holland", "author_id": "18387395", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Talking of unsupported assertions, when you call everyone here who disagrees with you \"astroturfers\", that's a very specific allegation. You're claiming that these people (including, no doubt, me) are fake posters, (probably) paid workers for some organisation, pretending to be something they are not. This is the accepted meaning of 'astroturf' in this context. From your previous accusations and obsessions, I assume that you are alleging they (we) are either from, or in the pay of, the Chinsese government.It would be good, given your dislike of \"misrepresentation, disinformation and exaggeration\", if you could share some of the evidence for this claim.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "113862233", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113866347", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521710949000}, "author": "dave6723", "author_id": "18522661", "schema_org_t