 this century was warmer than the El Ninos of comparable strength that occurred last century. In other words, while El Ninos are not \"AGW\" or anthropogenic global warming, the increase in the climate temperature increases the temperature of El Ninos.", "recommendation_count": "4", "in_reply_to": "113836566", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "global warming", "effect": "as this variation occurs around the rising climate temperature trend"}]}, {"id": "113858488", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521674641000}, "author": "Yetypu", "author_id": "4669086", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "Been doing it for over 40 years.", "recommendation_count": "0", "in_reply_to": "113849798", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113856816", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521668643000}, "author": "ElephantofTruth", "author_id": "4154310", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"I've said it before - the peer of a charlatan is a charlatan, whereas an Einstein has no peer. I don't have any problems with AGW per se, only with those who demand non-heretical adherence - that's a bit too 'born again' for me.\"\n\" I'd find it less offensive if they'd adopted 68%, or one sigma.\".\n\"Models can be science\"\nI am sorry but I haven't any 'answer' to these non-statements about the real processes involved in climate change. I'm sure Einstein would be very pleased you mention him. I hope you have a good time with your 'one sigma'.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "113845314", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113856392", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521667746000}, "author": "ElephantofTruth", "author_id": "4154310", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "\"Is there any predictive mathematical equation that uses real numbers in science that is not based on a model of some sort?\"\nI don't think so, no. I think an equation is a kind of model. The measurements that are fed into equations are of course produced by instruments. I think Gaston Bachelard says that scientific instruments are the embodiments of theories. Scientific enquiry is only possible if we have a 'model' in which the measurements made by instruments are actually related to things in the real world via a workable model. This is in the same way that the expansion or contraction of mercury is a 'proxy' for temperature. Research requires lots of work and replication and backtracking to produce reliable results, but it is perfectly possible. Everything is a work in progress. There is a naive view that there is some kind of raw data lying around waiting to be discovered - 'Hey I'm a piece of data, so discover me.' A naive belief in 'data' which doesn't have to be processed in some way seems to underlie the complaint that 'climate science is just models', 'they tweaked the data' etc. The inherent uncertainty in scientific enquiry is treated with suspicion rather than respect by those who prefer the bold certainties of other areas of publicly available debate.", "recommendation_count": "2", "in_reply_to": "113848008", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113855754", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521666320000}, "author": "TTauriStellarbody", "author_id": "16773618", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nAnother possible explanation is that RSS (the actual satellite experts) are right in their treatment of the fiendishly-difficult-to-process satellite data and UAH\nBQENDWho recommended this post its comical.\nThe text you quoted came from the page cited by GuyWarren in the OP, its taken from (drum roll please) \"RSS (the actual satellite experts)\".\nIf you have issues with it you can write to \" RSS (the actual satellite experts) \" and give them a piece of your mind. And you seriously responded to GuyWarren's link without reading it? Is this why you did not recognise where the quoted text had come from?\nBQSTART\nThe apparent discrepancy in lots of short-term sensitive stuff faded away once the Pacific belched out all that hea