 system by natural and anthropogenic forcing agents such as GHGs, aerosols, solar forcing and land use change. Forcing agents may be specified in various ways, for example, as emissions or as concentrations (see Section 12.2). The third is uncertainty related to the response of the climate system to the specified forcing agents.\nBQEND\nhttps://www.ipcc.ch/pdf/assessment-report/ar5/wg1/WG1AR5_Chapter11_FINAL.pdf\nPerhaps you can show us where the phrase \"accounted for\" is used in the literature?\nBQSTART\nis helping distribute lies and propaganda.\nBQENDWhy make their job easy with sloppy, invented statements?\nWell other than a neediness for attention?", "recommendation_count": "1", "in_reply_to": "113825482", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113835400", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521636776000}, "author": "TTauriStellarbody", "author_id": "16773618", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nThey outright deny climate science but the Democrats (and left/centrists everywhere) aren't actually that different to Trump.\nBQENDAnother of the \"left\"ish commentators who pretend that the US Demcrats are a bigger problem than Trump.\nFunny. \nBQSTART\nthey really care about is economic growth. If fossil fuels give them Jobz n Growth then stuff the environment!\nBQENDMore ignorance.\nThe US is currently producing GDP at about 1/3 the kgCO2/USD/year it did in 1970.\nGraph page 13http://www.globalcarbonproject.org/carbonbudget/17/files/GCP_CarbonBudget_2017.pdf\nAnd the rapid drop in costs of renewables and storage indicates that going low carbon will be great for growing economic activity in the coming decades.Perhaps constrain yourself to topics you have a basic knowledge off.", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "113834346", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113834512", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521635924000}, "author": "TTauriStellarbody", "author_id": "16773618", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nOver the past decade, we have been collaborating with Ben Santer at LLNL (along with numerous other investigators) to compare our tropospheric results with the predictions of climate models. Our results can be summarized as follows: \n Over the past 35 years, the troposphere has warmed significantly. The global average temperature has risen at an average rate of about 0.18 degrees Kelvin per decade (0.32 degrees F per decade). Climate models cannot explain this warming if human-caused increases in greenhouse gases are not included as input to the model simulation. The spatial pattern of warming is consistent with human-induced warming. See Santer et al 2008, 2009, 2011, and 2012 for more about the detection and attribution of human induced changes in atmospheric temperature using MSU/AMSU data.\n \nBut....\n The troposphere has not warmed quite as fast as most climate models predict. Note that this problem has been reduced by the large 2015-2106 El Nino Event, and the updated version of the RSS tropospheric datasets.\nBQEND\nBQSTART\nOne possible explanation is an error in the fundamental physics used by the climate models. In addition to this possibility, there are at least three other plausible explanations for the warming rate differences. There are errors in the forcings used as input to the model simulations (these include forcings due to anthropogenic gases and aerosols, volcanic aerosols, solar input, and changes in ozone), errors in the satellite observations (partially addressed by the use of the uncertainty ensemble), and sequences of internal climate variability in the simulations that are difference from what occurred in the real world. We call to these four explanations \u201cmodel physics errors\u201d, \u201cmodel input errors\u201d, \u201cobservational errors\u201d, and \u201cdifferent variability sequences\u201d. They are not mutually exclusive. In fact, t here is hard scientific evidence that all four of these factors contribute to the discrepancy, and that most of it can be explained without resorting to model physics errors.  For a detailed discussion of all these reasons, see the post on the Skeptical Science blog by Ben Santer and Carl Mears, and the recent paper in Nature Geoscience by Santer et al.\nBQEND", "recommendation_count": "3", "in_reply_to": "113831754", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "anthropogenic gases and aerosols volcanic aerosols", "effect": "forcings"}]}, {"id": "113834346", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521635756000}, "author": "uncommodified", "author_id": "18309811", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "It is meaningless to vilify the Trump team. They outright deny climate science but the Democrats (and left/centrists everywhere) aren't actually that different to Trump. All they really care about is economic growth. If fossil fuels give them Jobz n Growth then stuff the environment!\nPeople talk about Merkel and Trudeau as if they are environmental angels but they have still presided over massive expansions of dirty coal and oil fuel in their countries. What is the actual difference between them and Trump?", "recommendation_count": "2", "causal_relations": null}, {"id": "113832136", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521633123000}, "author": "dave6723", "author_id": "18522661", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nIf John Christy\u2019s criticism of the CMIP models is not acceptable\nBQEND\nDunno. Is it published in the peer-reviewed literature? I can only find a Wall Street Journal op-ed. The WSJ of course jumps to Uncle Rupert's strings. So only publishes denial pieces, interspersed with cherry-picked lukewarmer pieces in an effort to maintain some facade of credibility.\nSo if you're referring to his WSJ piece, no it's not acceptable. He and Judith Curry have a track record of carefully keeping their peer-reviewed literature reasonably straight but making statements in the press or to politicians that go 'way beyond what their peer-reviewed work supports. S