 of the lower stratosphere, while TLT estimates will include some surface temperature. These overlaps matter because different parts of the atmosphere are expected to react very differently to climate change.\n Because the tropospheric temperature estimates from satellites overlap with part of the stratosphere, they end up combining a bit of stratospheric cooling with tropospheric warming and can underestimate the true rate of warming. To avoid this issue, the new study applies a correction to remove some of the stratospheric cooling from the TMT series. The approach they use for this is described in a previous paper published in the Journal of Climate.\n\nBQENDEach of these sweeps is picking up an enormous lump of atmosphere with many things happening in it. The tropopause (where the tropsophere changes to the stratosphere can vary in altitude from about 17 to about 9km, that means that these layers will including differing parts of the atmosphere at differing latitudes.\nI think it is useful trying to get a mental picture of the tropopause changing over the distance from the equator to the Arctic\\Antarctic circles then think of the difficulties in inferring temperature trends from this giant chunk of sky across the whole planet.\nIts a tough bit of science but useful in backing up the surface record.\nBQENDThis covers Santer 2017\n\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/ngeo2973\n\nCauses of differences in model and satellite tropospheric warming rates\n\nBQSTART\n \nBQSTART\nSo what are the corrections made by the RSS team? As I mentioned earlier, the orbits of the satellites change over time which means that locations where measurements are made at a given time of the day change (it drifts). To account for these changes, RSS used a combination of satellite comparisons, climate models, and something called climate reanalysis to estimate changes in the temperature with time. They included measurements from other instruments as a check, such as weather balloons. RSS also identified bad data \u2013 when multiple measurements were made and one of the measurements disagreed substantially with the others, it was suspect. They also caught a calibration error that lead to changes in warming rate. \nBQEND\n0nly 15 instruments over 38 years. the instrument itself has calibration issues in that once it flies it has a hard time ensuring they get the degredation of the instrument right.\nBut this correction was dropping the satellites that had the most orbital drift.\nI think they dropped NOAA18 completely, NOAA 15 after 2011 and AQUA after 2009.\nI think (from Z Hausfather) the satellite data now shows warming 5% faster than the surface records from 1979.\nA cat among the pigeons to be sure.\nBQEND\nhttps://www.theguardian.com/environment/climate-consensus-97-per-cent/2017/jul/03/bad-news-for-climate-contrarians-the-best-data-we-have-just-got-hotter#comment-101434424\nAnd this covers the RSS updated dataset from Journal of ClimateMears Wentz 2017A Satellite-Derived Lower-Tropospheric Atmospheric Temperature Dataset Using an Optimized Adjustment for Diurnal Effects https://journals.ametsoc.org/doi/abs/10.1175/JCLI-D-16-0768.1", "recommendation_count": "7", "in_reply_to": "113813899", "causal_relations": [{"cause": "different parts of the atmosphere are expected to react very differently to climate change", "effect": "these overlaps matter"}, {"cause": "that", "effect": "changes in warming rate"}]}, {"id": "113831670", "time_stamp": {"$date": 1521632488000}, "author": "dave6723", "author_id": "18522661", "schema_org_type": "http://schema.org/Comment", "text": "BQSTART\nTo disbelieve climate change, you have to believe that the reported temperature data is valid and has not been tampered with to support a narrative. There are no reasons to doubt that. IOW you have to be a crackpot conspiracy theorist, in the same boat as flat-earthers, Birthers, Truthers, Bigfootists and Area 51 freaks. \nBQEND\nThere, fixed it for you.", "recommendation_count